        <p>So, if events <em style="bold">A and B are disjoint</em>, then (by definition) <em
                style="bold">P(A and B)= 0.</em> But what if the events are not disjoint? </p>
        <p>Recall that rule 4, the
            <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T151905-0500"?>A<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T151905-0500" content="a"?>ddition
            <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T151908-0500"?>R<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T151907-0500" content="r"?>ule,
            has two versions. One is restricted to disjoint events, which we've already covered, and
            we'll deal with the more general version later in this module.
            <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T151923-0500"?>The same is true of
            <?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T151933-0500" content="Exactly the same structure applies to "?>rule
            5. <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T151943-0500"?>Rule 5 has
            <?oxy_insert_end?>two<?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T151949-0500" content="It will have two"?>
            versions. The version we'll present here is restricted to a special case
            <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T152001-0500"?>that<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T152000-0500" content="which"?>
            we'll now discuss, and there is a more general version
            <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T152015-0500"?>that<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T152014-0500" content="which"?>
            we'll present in the next module.</p>
        <p>The version of rule 5
            <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T152044-0500"?>that<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T152042-0500" content="which"?>
            will be presented here applies to the special case
            <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T152059-0500"?>in
            which<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T152058-0500" content="when"?>
            the two events are <em>independent</em> of each other.</p>
        <!--:WARNING: The syntax of the definition element has changed.-->
        <!--Please verify that the translated output below is correct.-->
        <definition>
            <term>independent</term>
            <meaning>
                <material>
                    <p>Two events A and B are said to be <em>independent</em> if
                        <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T152207-0500"?><?oxy_comment_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T152702-0500" comment="Statistics is complicated enough without throwing quantum phisics into the mix ;)"?>the
                        fact
                        that<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T152303-0500" content="knowing whether"?><?oxy_comment_end?>
                        one event has occurred <em>does not affect</em> the probability that the
                        other event
                        <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T152725-0500"?>will
                        <?oxy_insert_end?>occur<?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T152727-0500" content="s"?>.
                        If whether
                        <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T153129-0500"?>or not
                        <?oxy_insert_end?>one event occurs <em>does affect</em> the probability that
                        the other event
                        <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T152745-0500"?>will
                        <?oxy_insert_end?>occur<?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T152747-0500" content="s"?>,
                        then the two events are said to be <em>dependent.</em>
                    </p>
                </material>
            </meaning>
        </definition>

        <p>Here are a few examples:</p>
        <example>

            <p>A woman's pocket contains two quarters and two nickels. She randomly extracts one of
                the coins and, after looking at it, replaces it before picking a second coin.</p>
            <p>Let Q1 be the event that the first coin is a quarter and Q2 be the event that the
                second coin is a quarter.</p>
            <p>Are Q1 and Q2 independent events?
                    <em>Y<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T152831-0500"?>es.<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T152829-0500" content="ES!"?></em>
                Why?</p>
            <p>Since the first coin that was selected is
                    <?oxy_comment_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T153454-0500" comment="remove bold. No emphasis needed"?><em>replaced</em><?oxy_comment_end?>,
                whether <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T153104-0500"?>or not
                <?oxy_insert_end?>Q1 occurred (i.e., whether the first coin was a quarter) has no
                effect on the probability that the second coin
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T152921-0500"?>will
                be<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T152922-0500" content="is"?>
                a quarter, P(Q2). In either case (whether Q1 occurred or not), when <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T152953-0500"?>she<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T152952-0500" content="we"?>
                <?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T152940-0500" content="come to "?><?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T153722-0500"?>is
                <?oxy_insert_end?>select<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T153725-0500"?>ing<?oxy_insert_end?>
                the second coin,
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T153016-0500"?>she
                has<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T153014-0500" content="we have"?>
                in
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T153028-0500"?>her<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T153029-0500" content="our"?>
                pocket:</p>
            <image style="block" src="../webcontent/image020.gif" alt="The coins in the woman's pocket.
There are 2 Quarters and 2 Nickels."/>
            <p>and therefore the P(Q2)<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T153044-0500"?>
                <?oxy_insert_end?>=<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T153044-0500"?>
                <?oxy_insert_end?>2/4<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T153045-0500"?>
                <?oxy_insert_end?>=<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T153046-0500"?>
                <?oxy_insert_end?>1/2 regardless of whether Q1 occurred.</p>
        </example>
        <example>

            <p>A woman's pocket contains two quarters and two nickels. She randomly extracts one of
                the
                coins<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T153247-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
                and
                    <?oxy_comment_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T153314-0500" comment="remove bold -- no emphasis needed"?><em>without
                    placing</em><?oxy_comment_end?> it back into her pocket, she picks a second
                coin. As before, let Q1 be the event that the first coin is a quarter, and Q2 be the
                event that the second coin is a quarter.</p>
            <p>Are Q1 and Q2 independent events?
                    <em>N<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T153333-0500"?>o.<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T153330-0500" content="O!"?></em>
                Q1 and Q2 are <em>not independent</em>. They are <em>dependent.</em> Why?</p>
            <p>Since the first coin that was selected is
                    <?oxy_comment_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T153406-0500" comment="remove bold -- no emphasis needed"?><em>not
                    replaced,</em><?oxy_comment_end?> whether Q1 occurred (i.e., whether the first
                coin was a quarter) <em>does affect</em> the probability that the second coin is a
                quarter, P(Q2).</p>
            <p>If Q1 occurred (i.e., the first coin was a quarter), then when
                <?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T153644-0500" content="we come to"?><?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T153644-0500"?>the woman<?oxy_insert_end?>
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T153712-0500"?>is
                <?oxy_insert_end?>select<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T153714-0500"?>ing<?oxy_insert_end?>
                the second coin,
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T153658-0500"?>she
                has<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T153742-0500" content="we have"?>
                in
                <?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T153747-0500" content="our"?><?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T153748-0500"?>her<?oxy_insert_end?>
                pocket:</p>
            <image style="block" src="../webcontent/image021.gif" alt="One Quarter and Two Nickels"/>
            <p><?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T153804-0500"?>I<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T153803-0500" content="i"?>n
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T153807-0500"?>this<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T153811-0500" content="which"?>
                case<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T154022-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?> P(Q2)<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T153836-0500"?>
                <?oxy_insert_end?>=<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T153836-0500"?>
                <?oxy_insert_end?>1/3. However, if Q1 has not occurred (i.e., the first coin was not
                a
                quarter<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T153857-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
                but a nickel), then when
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T153936-0500"?>the woman
                is<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T153941-0500" content="we come to"?>
                select<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T153944-0500"?>ing<?oxy_insert_end?>
                the second coin,
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T153949-0500"?>she
                has<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T153951-0500" content="we have"?>
                in
                <?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T153954-0500" content="our"?><?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T153955-0500"?>her<?oxy_insert_end?>
                pocket:</p>
            <image style="block" src="../webcontent/image022.gif" alt="Two Quarters and One Nickel."/>
            <p><?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T154006-0500"?>I<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T154004-0500" content="i"?>n
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T154008-0500"?>this<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T154009-0500" content="which"?>
                case<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T154018-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?> P(Q2)<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T154025-0500"?>
                <?oxy_insert_end?>=<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T154026-0500"?>
                <?oxy_insert_end?>2/3.</p>
            <p>In these last two examples, we could actually
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T154110-0500"?>have
                done<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T154114-0500" content="do"?>
                some calculation in order to check whether or not the two events are independent or
                not. Sometimes we can just use common sense to guide us as to whether two events are
                independent. Here is an example.</p>
        </example>

        <example>

            <p>A family has 4 children, two of whom are selected at random. Let B1 be the event that
                <?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T172716-0500" content="the first "?><?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101130T152640-0500"?>one<?oxy_insert_end?>
                child has blue eyes, and B2 be the event that the
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T160843-0500"?>other<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T160842-0500" content="second"?>
                chosen child has blue eyes. In this
                case<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T154234-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
                B1 and B2 are not
                independent<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T154301-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
                since we know that eye color is hereditary, so whether
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T154313-0500"?>or not
                one<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T160905-0500" content="the first"?>
                child is blue-eyed will increase or decrease the chances that the
                <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T160916-0500"?>other<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T160911-0500" content="second"?>
                child has blue eyes, respectively.</p>
        </example>

        <example>

            <p><?oxy_comment_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T155321-0500" comment="I rewrote this to reflect the fact that if the two aren&apos;t chosen simultaneously, as a pair, the second choice is dependent on the first.(Once you choose one blue-eyed person, there will be one less blue-eyed person in the population you are choosing from, so the chances of choosing a blue-eyed person are lower.)
                
Alternatively, you could specify that you are re-insterting the first person back into the population before making your second choice.

Saying that the population is &quot;very large&quot; makes the mathematical effect of the removal of one member of the population minimal, but it does not eliminate it. 

I think that not including one or the other of these qualifiers will confuse students, because if you do not, this example contradicts the one about coins in your pocket. The only difference is that there the population is 4, and here it is millions.

On page 7 of probability rules, I have suggested a place to insert a comment about how it is OK to assume that events are independent in very large populations because of the negligible mathematical consequences. I recommend placing that comment there, rather than here, to give students a chance to get used to the difference between dependent and independent events before adding a &quot;special case.&quot; In between here and there, I have recommended changing wording to &quot;simultaneously and at random or adding &quot;with replacement.&quot;

