        <p><em style="bold">Note:</em></p>
        <p>We can generalize what we learned in the last example and say that when two individuals
            are selected at random from a large population (like in the example, the entire U.S.)
            any event associated with one individual is independent of any event associated with the
            other individual. The fact that the two are chosen from a large population is key to the
            independence.</p>

        <p>If we were to change the example to: There are 10 people in a room, 4 of which have blue
            eyes. Two people are chosen at random. Let B1 be the event that the first person has
            blue eyes and let B2 be the event that the second person has blue eyes. In this case,
            since the two are chosen from a group of only 10 (rather than a large population) the
            events B1 and B2 are not independent. Clearly, whether or not the first person has blue
            eyes (i.e., whether or not B1 occurs) does have an effect on whether B2 occurs. You will
            get more practice on this point in the activities below the next comment. </p>
        <section>
            <title>Comment</title>
            <body>
                <p>It is quite common for students to initially get confused about the distinction
                    between the idea of <em>disjoint events</em> and the idea of <em>independent
                        events</em>. The purpose of this comment (and the activity that follows it)
                    is to help students develop more understanding about
                    these<?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T173832-0500" content=" two"?>
                    very different ideas. </p>
                <p>The idea of <em>disjoint events</em> is about whether or not it is possible for
                    the<?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T161107-0500" content=" two"?>
                    events
                    <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T161007-0500"?>to<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T161006-0500" content="can"?>
                    occur at the same time (see
                    <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T161014-0500"?>the
                    <?oxy_insert_end?>examples on page 3 of
                    <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T161229-0500"?>the
                    <?oxy_insert_end?>Probability
                    Rules<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T161232-0500"?>
                    section<?oxy_insert_end?>).</p>
                <p>The idea of <em>independent events</em> is about whether or not
                    the<?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T161359-0500" content=" two"?>
                    events affect each other in the sense that the occurrence of one event affects
                    the probability of the occurrence of the other (see
                    <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T161323-0500"?>the
                    <?oxy_insert_end?>examples above).</p>
                <p>The following activity deals with the distinction between
                    these<?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T161333-0500" content=" two"?>
                    concepts.</p>

            </body>
        </section>
        <!--<activity idref="_u4_m1_lbd6" purpose="learnbydoing"/>-->
        <p>The purpose of this activity is to help you strengthen your understanding about the
            concepts of disjoint events and independent events, and the distinction between
            them.</p>
        <section purpose="learnbydoing">
            <title></title>
            <body>
                <p>In each of the following
                    questions<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T161454-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
                    you are presented with a random experiment and two events related to it. You are
                    asked to decide whether the
                    <?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T161510-0500" content="two "?>events
                    are disjoint or
                    not<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101108T161515-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
                    and whether the events are independent or not.</p>
                <wb:inline idref="u3_m1_rules5_tutor2" purpose="learnbydoing"/>
                <!--   <wb:inline idref="u3_m1_rules5_tutor3" purpose="learnbydoing"/>-->
            </body>
        </section>
        <section>
            <title/>
            <body>
                <p>Let’s summarize the three parts of the activity:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>In Example 1: A and B are <em style="bold">not disjoint</em> and <em
                            style="bold">independent</em></li>
                    <li>In Example 2: A and B are <em style="bold">not disjoint</em> and <em
                            style="bold">not independent</em></li>
                    <li>In Example 3: A and B are <em style="bold">disjoint</em> and <em
                            style="bold">not independent</em>.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Why did we leave out the case when the events are disjoint and independent? The
                    reason is that this case DOES NOT EXIST!</p>
               <!--  <image style="block" src="../webcontent/disjoint_not.png" alt="A table showing the
relationship between independent and disjoint events. The column headings are: &quot;A,B Independent
&quot; and &quot;A,B Not Independent.&quot; The row headings are &quot;A,B Disjoint&quot; and
&quot;A,B Not Disjoint.&quot; Here are the cells of the table in &quot;Row, Column: Value&quot;
format:
    A,B Disjoint, A,B Independent: DOES NOT EXIST;
    A,B Disjoint, A,B Not Independent: Example 3;
    A,B Not Disjoint, A,B Independent: Example 1;
    A,B Not Disjoint, A,B Not Independent: Example 2;"/>--> 
                <table>
                    <tr><td></td>
                        <td><em style="bold">A and B Independent</em></td>
                        <td><em style="bold">A and B Not Independent</em></td></tr>
                    <tr><td><em style="bold">A and B Disjoint</em></td>
                        <td><em style="highlight">DOES NOT EXIST</em></td>
                        <td>Example 3</td></tr>
                    <tr><td><em style="bold">A and B Not Disjoint</em></td>
                        <td>Example 1</td>
                        <td>Example 2</td></tr>
                </table>
                <p>If events are <em style="bold">disjoint</em> then they <em style="bold">must be
                        not independent (dependent)</em></p>
                <p>Why is that?</p>
                <p>Recall: A and B disjoint means that they cannot happen together. In other words, A and B
                    disjoint implies that if event A occurs then B does not and vice versa. Well… if
                    that’s the case, knowing that event A has occurred dramatically changes the
                    likelihood that event B occurs – that likelihood is <m:math display = 'inline'>
                        <m:mrow>
                            <m:mn>0</m:mn>
                        </m:mrow>
                    </m:math>. This implies that A and B
                    are not independent.</p>
            </body>
        </section>

        <section purpose="didigetthis">
            <title/>
            <body>
                <wb:inline idref="u3_m1_rules5_tutor4" purpose="didigetthis"/>
                <wb:inline idref="u3_m1_rules5_tutor5" purpose="didigetthis"/>
            </body>
        </section>
        <p>Now that we understand the idea of independent events, we can finally get to rule 5. As
            mentioned before, Rule 5 actually has two versions, one for finding P(A and B) in the
